00:27:59,120 --> 00:28:05,320
  Are you happy, Clarissa? 
 Does Richard ...

240
00:28:05,360 --> 00:28:08,560
  Excuse me, ma'am. The gentlemen
 are here from Rumplemayers.

241
00:28:08,600 --> 00:28:10,520
  Oh, thank you, Lucy.

242
00:28:13,800 --> 00:28:15,160
  Good bye, Clarissa.

243
00:28:25,320 --> 00:28:26,840
  My party tonight

244
00:28:27,440 --> 00:28:30,160
  Please come to my party, 
 tonight.

245
00:29:29,920 --> 00:29:31,880
  Come on! Let's get out of this.

246
00:29:31,960 --> 00:29:33,280
  I want to do another!

247
00:29:33,600 --> 00:29:34,520
  Come on.

248
00:29:40,040 --> 00:29:43,880
Is this what you want? 
 Staying here and go to parties?

249
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:47,440
  But I like parties! 
 Oh, Clarissa!

250
00:30:29,960 --> 00:30:32,360
  You always tie me up
with your queen standard, Breitl.

251
00:30:32,520 --> 00:30:34,400
  It's my turn to shuffle, 
 Herbert.

252
00:30:35,600 --> 00:30:38,280
  Hugh, do you  
ever stop eating?

253
00:30:41,080 --> 00:30:43,320
  Did you know 
Wingate's married again?

254
00:30:43,480 --> 00:30:46,160
  Yes, they came to call 
last week.

255
00:30:46,240 --> 00:30:49,240
  The woman use to be his housemaid.

256
00:30:49,520 --> 00:30:52,920
He had a nerve. 
 Bringing a housemaid to Cork.

257
00:30:53,320 --> 00:30:58,000
 Yes! She was absurdly overdressed. 
She looked like a cockatoo.

258
00:30:58,040 --> 00:30:59,520
  And she never stopped talking!

259
00:31:00,120 --> 00:31:02,080
  She probably thought 
you all knew.

260
00:31:02,800 --> 00:31:04,080
 Knew what?

261
00:31:05,480 --> 00:31:08,000
  That she had a baby
 before she was married.

262
00:31:14,280 --> 00:31:18,840
  - I don't think I should ever be up to speak to her again! 
 - Don't be ridiculous, Clarissa.

263
00:31:19,480 --> 00:31:23,800
  If this is true we should certainly
 not receive her again.

264
00:31:23,840 --> 00:31:28,480
  I should think not. If we start receiving 
  women like that, you don't know where it'll end?

265
00:31:28,680 --> 00:31:33,640
  Oh, you snob! You represent all that's 
 detestable in british middle class life.

266
00:31:33,680 --> 00:31:37,080
  It's men like you who's responsible 
 for prostitutes around Piccadilly.

267
00:31:37,120 --> 00:31:40,280
  Me! 
 Yes, men like you.

268
00:31:40,320 --> 00:31:43,720
  That's enough, Sally. We'll have no more  
 of this conversation.

269
00:31:55,760 --> 00:31:59,920
  I'm glad I walked out. They're all 
 such snobs and Hugh is a fraud.

270
00:31:59,920 --> 00:32:02,120
  Clarissa is so prudish 
 and arrogant.

271
00:32:03,120 --> 00:32:04,280
  Not really.

272
00:32:05,960 --> 00:32:10,800
 It's just what she's been brought up to. 
 Wish she would see things more clearly.

273
00:32:12,320 --> 00:32:14,560
  Clearly enough to marry you, 
you mean?

274
00:32:39,280 --> 00:32:40,440
  I see.

275
00:32:42,520 --> 00:32:46,880
  This is Mr. Wickham, Peter. 
 My name is Dalloway.

276
00:32:47,640 --> 00:32:49,360
  Richard Dalloway.

277
00:32:50,880 --> 00:32:53,360
  But I've introduced you
to everyone as Mr. Wickham.

278
00:32:54,280 --> 00:32:58,120
 Still Dalloway. 
 My name is Dalloway.

279
00:32:58,200 --> 00:32:59,360
  Dalloway.

280
00:33:04,360 --> 00:33:06,520
 So definitly you're going
to go to politics?

281
00:33:06,640 --> 00:33:10,200
  Yes, I think so. 
 What is with your friend, Mr. ..?

282
00:33:10,720 --> 00:33:12,360
  "My name is Dalloway".

283
00:33:14,360 --> 00:33:15,760
  What's the matter?

284
00:33:16,400 --> 00:33:18,880
  Somebody's just walking 
 on my grave.

285
00:33:18,920 --> 00:33:23,120
  I took another friend. 
 She's gonna marry that man!

286
00:33:45,800 --> 00:33:47,240
  I went into the sea.

287
00:33:49,280 --> 00:33:50,800
  I have been dead.

288
00:33:53,520 --> 00:33:55,520
  But now I'm alive.

289
00:34:01,480 --> 00:34:03,760
  I must rest, I must rest.

290
00:34:05,080 --> 00:34:07,680
  Septimus, I'm going to ask 
 someone the time.

291
00:34:07,960 --> 00:34:09,680
  I think we have to go now.

292
00:34:10,080 --> 00:34:13,680
  It's nowhere to go, 
nowhere to hide.

293
00:34:13,720 --> 00:34:16,720
  Septimus, you know we are going to see 
 a doctor who will help you.

294
00:34:16,760 --> 00:34:18,320
  No more doctors!

295
00:34:18,960 --> 00:34:21,720
  No more lies! 
 Septimus, please!

296
00:34:24,640 --> 00:34:25,680
  Irvin!

297
00:34:31,000 --> 00:34:32,400
  Thank you.

298
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:44,040
  Evans?

299
00:34:47,160 --> 00:34:48,560
  Evans!

300
00:34:50,200 --> 00:34:52,720
  For God's sake, don't come!

301
00:35:08,600 --> 00:35:12,000
  Septimus, it isn't Evans, allright? 
 It isn't Evans.

302
00:35:12,040 --> 00:35:15,360
  There is nothing to worry about. 
 The man is not Evans.

303
00:35:19,320 --> 00:35:20,880
Really, he isn't.

304
00:35:22,200 --> 00:35:23,480
  Come on.

305
00:35:24,360 --> 00:35:25,560
  Let's go for a walk.

306
00:35:39,200 --> 00:35:42,360
  Clarissa! It's such a lovely evening. 
 Let's go to the lake.

307
00:35:42,400 --> 00:35:43,800
  Yes! We can go boating.

308
00:35:44,800 --> 00:35:47,120
  Let's get our shoulds. 
 It might be cold.

309
00:35:54,840 --> 00:35:57,840
  Peter! We're going boating
 on the lake. Aren't you coming?

310
00:36:08,800 --> 00:36:11,680
  I think Mr. Dalloway 
 likes you.

311
00:36:13,600 --> 00:36:16,200
Oh, aren't we being 
 the perfect hostess?

312
00:36:16,520 --> 00:36:19,480
Oh, don't come than if you're going 
to be beastly in the wood.

313
00:36:19,640 --> 00:36:22,920
  "Dalloway. It's still Dalloway."

314
00:36:39,680 --> 00:36:40,720
  Come on.

315
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:43,680
  They're all waiting.

316
00:38:29,600 --> 00:38:30,680
  Poor old woman.

317
00:38:33,560 --> 00:38:36,320
  Septimus, you won't tell 
 the doctor, will you?

318
00:38:36,520 --> 00:38:39,920
  You mustn't. 
 They will take you away from me.

319
00:38:53,800 --> 00:38:56,600
  Sir William BRADSHAW 
 M.D.

320
00:38:57,040 --> 00:39:02,520
 I've looked at Dr. Holmes's notes. 
 He's been seeing your husband for some six weeks?

321
00:39:02,560 --> 00:39:05,600
  Yes. 
 He is our landlady's doctor.

322
00:39:05,920 --> 00:39:09,480
  She send for him because 
 I told her I was worried about Septimus.

323
00:39:09,840 --> 00:39:12,760
  He threatened to kill himself? 
 He didn't mean it.

324
00:39:12,800 --> 00:39:15,800
  No. Of course not.

325
00:39:15,840 --> 00:39:19,320
  And Dr. Holmes prescribed ...

326
00:39:20,280 --> 00:39:22,360
  bromine? 
 Yes

327
00:39:23,920 --> 00:39:26,320
 He said that there was nothing really wrong. 


328
00:39:30,640 --> 00:39:35,480

But Septimus keeps talking to the dead man, Evans, 
his friend who was killed in the war. 


329
00:39:36,120 --> 00:39:39,800
 And Septimus wasn't like this
 when I met him.

330
00:39:40,480 --> 00:39:43,120
 It's happened in just the last few months.

331
00:39:44,880 --> 00:39:47,920
  He says people are talking 
 behind bedroom walls...

332
00:39:47,960 --> 00:39:51,480
  and he saw a woman's head
 in the middle of a fern.

333
00:39:52,040 --> 00:39:54,720
  He says he's on trial  
 for some terrible crime ...

334
00:39:54,760 --> 00:39:56,240
  but, of course, he's done nothing.

335
00:39:56,240 --> 00:40:01,200
 And then he seems to forget 
it all and seems happy again, as he used to be.

336
00:40:01,400 --> 00:40:04,120
  We went to Hampton Court, 
on top of a bus, the other day...

337
00:40:04,160 --> 00:40:08,480
  and told of red and yellow flowers. He said 
they looked like floating lamps.

338
00:40:08,520 --> 00:40:12,120
 And he was fun, as he used to be  
 and made me laugh. I was so happy.

339
00:40:12,160 --> 00:40:16,080
  And suddenly, as we  
 were standing by the river, he said ...

340
00:40:16,120 --> 00:40:19,800
  "We will kill ourselves." 
 Then, he held my hand ...

341
00:40:19,840 --> 00:40:23,440
  and said he was falling
 into the flames. And he cried and cried.

342
00:40:27,120 --> 00:40:32,160
  Ms. Warrensmith, your husband is  
 very seriously ill.

343
00:40:32,560 --> 00:40:36,240
  From everything you told me  
 and from Dr. Holmes's report ...

344
00:40:36,280 --> 00:40:40,240
  I believe that his suffering
from delayed shell shock.

345
00:40:40,280 --> 00:40:41,640
  But he's not mad, is he?

346
00:40:42,040 --> 00:40:45,720
  I never use that word. 
 I prefer to say ...

347
00:40:46,000 --> 00:40:48,000
lacking the sense of proportion.

348
00:40:48,040 --> 00:40:51,560
  But Dr. Holmes said that there
  was nothing what so ever the matter!

349
00:40:51,600 --> 00:40:55,600
  Your husband needs rest. 
Complete rest.

350
00:40:55,600 --> 00:40:57,040
But not away from me!

351
00:40:57,680 --> 00:41:02,960
  My dear Ms. Warrensmith sometimes 
we have to separate such people...

352
00:41:03,000 --> 00:41:06,080
from their loved ones, 
for their own good.

353
00:41:19,120 --> 00:41:22,280
  Dalloway! I met Clarissa 
 this morning.

354
00:41:22,320 --> 00:41:25,880
So, she's giving another of her 
famous parties tonight?

355
00:41:26,840 --> 00:41:28,280
  Right as usual, Hugh.

356
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:33,680
  And Lady Bruton summond you as well. 
 Wonder what she wants from us?

357
00:41:33,720 --> 00:41:37,120
  Nothing we can't accomplish 
 ever at a good lunch, I'm sure.

358
00:41:38,200 --> 00:41:40,560
  Ah, good day, Miss Brasher. 
 Good day, sir.

359
00:41:40,600 --> 00:41:43,000
  How's your brother, 
 in South Africa?

360
00:41:45,000 --> 00:41:49,920
 I got you here under false pretenses. 
I actually need your help.

361
00:41:50,040 --> 00:41:51,720
  But we'll have lunch first.

362
00:41:54,840 --> 00:41:56,400
  And how is Clarissa?

363
00:41:56,920 --> 00:42:00,920
Quite well recovered, thank you. 
 The doctor told her he must take things easy ...

364
00:42:00,960 --> 00:42:03,960
  But she does so want to
give her party tonight.

365
00:42:04,120 --> 00:42:07,520
  I trust we'll should have the pleasure 
 of your company tonight.

366
00:42:07,560 --> 00:42:10,920
  Of course, Richard. I wouldn't miss 
 one of your parties.

367
00:42:11,400 --> 00:42:14,160
  I met Clarissa in the park 
 this morning.

368
00:42:14,240 --> 00:42:17,480
  She was wearing  
a yellow feathered hat.

369
00:42:17,520 --> 00:42:20,200
  Oh, yes! I like that hat.

370
00:42:30,520 --> 00:42:32,320
 We'll you come in now, please?

371
00:42:40,520 --> 00:42:41,600
  Good.

372
00:42:46,320 --> 00:42:47,840
  Do sit down.

373
00:42:52,680 --> 00:42:58,360
  I see that you served with great distinction 
in the war, Mr. Warrensmith.

374
00:42:58,960 --> 00:43:00,000
  At the war?

375
00:43:01,320 --> 00:43:03,400
  The European war.

376
00:43:04,320 --> 00:43:07,320
  A little shindy of schoolboys 
 with gunpowder.

377
00:43:07,880 --> 00:43:10,960
  Did I serve with distinction? 
 I'd forgotten.

378
00:43:11,040 --> 00:43:14,480
  In the war, itself, I failed.

379
00:43:14,520 --> 00:43:18,720
  No, he served with the greatest distinction. 
 He was promoted.

380
00:43:19,600 --> 00:43:20,720
  I. ..

381
00:43:22,480 --> 00:43:26,760
  I have committed a crime. 
 He's done nothing wrong whatever.

382
00:43:27,440 --> 00:43:31,720
  What did Dr. Holmes advised 
you to do?

383
00:43:32,040 --> 00:43:34,400
 To my wife he said
to make me porridge.

384
00:43:36,200 --> 00:43:38,960
  Headache, dreams, 
 fears are just nerves.

385
00:43:39,120 --> 00:43:41,440
  Health is largely a  
matter of our control.

386
00:43:41,480 --> 00:43:42,760
  I should take up some hobby.

387
00:43:44,600 --> 00:43:46,080
  Dr. Holmes ...

388
00:43:48,640 --> 00:43:53,240
 throws himself into outside interests. 
 And throwing himself, he is able ...

389
00:43:53,280 --> 00:43:57,000
  to switch off from his patients  
 on to old furniture.

390
00:43:57,040 --> 00:43:59,560
  Dr. Holmes is interested 
 in antique furniture.

391
00:43:59,840 --> 00:44:01,080
  Yes

392
00:44:01,120 --> 00:44:04,080
 So, when the damn fool came again, 
 I refused to see him.

393
00:44:04,360 --> 00:44:05,720
  Impulsive brute...

394
00:44:06,840 --> 00:44:08,520
 Blood red nostrils...

395
00:44:09,520 --> 00:44:13,880
  Once you stumble, human nature 
 is on you. Holmes is on you.

396
00:44:14,760 --> 00:44:18,360
  Our only chance is to escape 
 without letting Holmes know.

397
00:44:18,840 --> 00:44:21,400
  Anywhere, 
 away from Dr. Holmes.

398
00:44:23,840 --> 00:44:27,680
  There is no excuse. 
Nothing whatever is the matter.

399
00:44:34,200 --> 00:44:35,840
  Except sin.

400
00:44:37,920 --> 00:44:39,280
  For which ...

401
00:44:39,600 --> 00:44:42,680
  human nature has condemned me 
to death.

402
00:44:44,880 --> 00:44:47,600
  I can not feel.

403
00:44:50,280 --> 00:44:53,160
  I did not care, 
 when  Evans was killed.

404
00:44:53,200 --> 00:44:54,400
  That was the worst ...

405
00:44:56,680 --> 00:44:58,520
  but all the other crimes ...

406
00:45:00,840 --> 00:45:05,840
  raised their heads, 
 shaked their fingers ...

407
00:45:06,560 --> 00:45:09,360
  and they cheer and they sneer.

408
00:45:10,760 --> 00:45:13,720
  And the verdict of human nature 
 on such a beast ...

409
00:45:13,760 --> 00:45:15,040
  is death!

410
00:45:23,400 --> 00:45:26,560
  We all have our moments 
 of depression.

411
00:45:30,320 --> 00:45:34,280
 He has impulses, sometimes? 
 That is my own affair!

412
00:45:34,440 --> 00:45:40,360
  There you are mistaken, sir. We are all 
responsible one for another.

413
00:45:41,840 --> 00:45:44,360
  I am responsible 
 to Dr. Holmes?

414
00:45:48,400 --> 00:45:49,760
  Another humbug.

415
00:45:52,880 --> 00:45:55,000
  We ...

416
00:45:55,320 --> 00:45:58,120
have been arranging
that you should go into a home.

417
00:45:58,160 --> 00:45:59,960
One of Holmes's homes?

418
00:46:00,600 --> 00:46:03,480
  No, one of my homes, 
 Mr. Warrensmith.

419
00:46:03,560 --> 00:46:08,800
  And there we will teach you to rest 
and to regain a sense of proportion.

420
00:46:08,840 --> 00:46:13,400
  But I've confessed! 
I confessed my crimes!

421
00:46:13,800 --> 00:46:18,160
  Why won't you had me off? 
 He's done nothing. Nothing!

422
00:46:18,200 --> 00:46:22,360
 He will be perfectly looked after. 
 I will visit once a week.

423
00:46:22,400 --> 00:46:25,200
  But my husband does not like 
 doctors. He will refuse to go.

424
00:46:25,240 --> 00:46:31,880
 Your husband has threatened to kill himself. 
There is no alternative, it is a question of the law.

425
00:46:32,800 --> 00:46:37,280
 It's a very beautiful home in the country. 
 Nurses are admirable.

426
00:46:37,320 --> 00:46:40,840
Now, if you have no further questions to ask...

427
00:46:40,880 --> 00:46:44,200
I will arrange everything with Dr. Holmes.

428
00:46:44,240 --> 00:46:47,320
He will send somebody around this evening ...

429
00:46:47,680 --> 00:46:49,400
  between five and six.

430
00:46:50,800 --> 00:46:53,560
 It's the law, Ms. Warrensmith, 
 and it is for the best.

431
00:46:53,600 --> 00:46:55,920
 It won't be Dr. Holmes who comes, will it?

432
00:46:55,920 --> 00:46:58,040
 Trust everything to me.

433
00:47:02,640 --> 00:47:06,280
I do not like that man. 
 He's a humbug.

434
00:47:14,160 --> 00:47:15,600
We are deserted.

435
00:47:24,400 --> 00:47:29,120
  Do you know who's in town?
 Our old friend, Peter Walsh.

436
00:47:29,440 --> 00:47:32,720
Back from India. 
 Peter Walsh back?

437
00:47:32,760 --> 00:47:35,000
  In trouble with some woman, 
evidently.

438
00:47:35,280 --> 00:47:37,080
  Some woman in India.

439
00:47:37,560 --> 00:47:40,200
  Peter Walsh was always in trouble 
 of some sort.

440
00:47:41,680 --> 00:47:44,440
Didn't he marry someone on the boat
going out?

441
00:47:44,480 --> 00:47:48,560
  I don't believe that lasted long. 
 I imagine that was all what...

442
00:47:48,560 --> 00:47:50,840
  I believe is known as "the rebound".

443
00:47:51,840 --> 00:47:54,040
  I suppose he'll try 
to settle here now.

444
00:47:54,320 --> 00:47:57,760
  I'd say it will be difficult to help him. 
He'll be quite a misfit.

445
00:47:58,640 --> 00:48:01,840
 I'm sure Clarissa will know 
that he's here.

446
00:48:01,920 --> 00:48:06,800
  And I no doubt he'll be at her the party 
tonight and all will be revealed.

447
00:48:07,080 --> 00:48:12,120
  Yes, if Peter Walsh is in town, 
 Clarissa will know.

448
00:48:20,520 --> 00:48:21,960
  This is better.

449
00:48:34,960 --> 00:48:36,320
  Come on, Peter.

450
00:48:40,440 --> 00:48:42,200
  We'll race you
 to the top.

451
00:48:53,720 --> 00:48:54,600
  Well ..

452
00:48:56,160 --> 00:48:57,920
  my idea is this.

453
00:48:58,120 --> 00:49:01,760
  We all agree, do we not,
 that Britain is overpopulated.

454
00:49:01,800 --> 00:49:03,240
  Yes, indeed.

455
00:49:03,320 --> 00:49:05,880
  And you agree ...

456
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:08,160
  that many of these men, 
 back from the war ...

457
00:49:08,200 --> 00:49:10,720
  are finding it difficult
 to find employment.

458
00:49:10,760 --> 00:49:13,200
Indeed, in some cases, 
their work ...

459
00:49:13,240 --> 00:49:16,600
  has been commandered by women. 
 However ...

460
00:49:16,600 --> 00:49:19,120
 We all know the rot
 that's set in there.

461
00:49:19,320 --> 00:49:21,920
  Unfortunately! 
 Well ..

462
00:49:22,680 --> 00:49:24,920
  my idea is a simple one.

463
00:49:25,200 --> 00:49:28,760
  All the best ideas are simple, 
as we know.

464
00:49:28,800 --> 00:49:31,760
  My project is to incourage ...

465
00:49:32,120 --> 00:49:36,160
 by making it financialy easy 
 young people of both sexes ...

466
00:49:36,920 --> 00:49:38,680
  to emigrate to Canada.

467
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:42,120
They will be set up with the fair chance 
of doing well in Canada.

468
00:49:42,360 --> 00:49:46,880
  And Britain will gain financialy, 
in the long run.

469
00:49:48,840 --> 00:49:52,760
It's only so much that I can do, 
being a woman.

470
00:49:53,160 --> 00:49:55,840
  But Richard, I ask you ...

471
00:49:56,160 --> 00:49:59,800
 to make this suggestion 
 in the House. And Hugh ...

472
00:49:59,840 --> 00:50:03,960
  I want you to help me start the ball rolling 
with a letter to the Times.

473
00:50:04,000 --> 00:50:07,960
  I know, my dear Hugh, 
 that you will know, exactly ...

474
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:09,400
  how to phrase it for me.

475
00:50:15,480 --> 00:50:19,320
  I think someone is already typing
a motion against some kind of emigration plan going.

476
00:50:19,360 --> 00:50:22,320
  But I suppose a letter to the Times 
 will do no harm.

