considering how ill she's been.

712
01:14:25,520 --> 01:14:28,400
 I know that Richard was very 
 worried about her.

713
01:14:28,440 --> 01:14:31,000
  M.P.'s wives 
really shouldn't get ill.

714
01:14:31,360 --> 01:14:33,960
  I believe it was her heart.

715
01:14:34,000 --> 01:14:37,680
  I think you can always pull yourself together. 
 Mind of a matter.

716
01:14:37,720 --> 01:14:43,240
  Harry Audle. 
You painted your wife. Lovely picture.

717
01:14:48,040 --> 01:14:49,040
  Peter!

718
01:14:50,800 --> 01:14:52,240
  Peter Walsh!

719
01:14:55,880 --> 01:15:01,080
  Good Lord! Sally Seaton. 
 Lady Rosseter now.

720
01:15:01,560 --> 01:15:05,560
  Don't be absurd. 
 It's true. Lady Rosseter.

721
01:15:06,600 --> 01:15:09,960
  We live in Manchester 
and I have five ennormous boys.

722
01:15:11,440 --> 01:15:16,080
  Either my eyes are deceiving me, 
 or that's Ellie Henderson?

723
01:15:16,320 --> 01:15:20,960
  It's our old vicar's daughter. 
 She's gaping at the Prime Minister.

724
01:15:21,000 --> 01:15:23,800
  Oh, do bring her over, 
 before she disgraces herself ...

725
01:15:23,840 --> 01:15:25,320
  and faints with astonishment.

726
01:15:29,720 --> 01:15:34,200
  Mr. Prime Minister, how nice to see you. 
 What would you like?

727
01:15:34,240 --> 01:15:38,160
  She's always looked delicate to me. 
 But such charm.

728
01:15:38,200 --> 01:15:40,600
  Richard would've done a great deal better, 
if he'd married a woman ...

729
01:15:40,640 --> 01:15:44,920
   with less charm and more backbone. 
 It would've helped him in his work.

730
01:15:45,200 --> 01:15:47,160
  He's lost his chance in the Cabinet.

731
01:15:49,680 --> 01:15:52,120
  Lady Bruton and Lady Beckford.

732
01:15:52,160 --> 01:15:53,560
  What a pleasure to see you.

733
01:15:54,840 --> 01:15:57,320
  Lord, what snobbs the english are!

734
01:15:58,080 --> 01:16:02,200
 How they love dressing up 
 and doing homage. Listen to them!

735
01:16:06,800 --> 01:16:10,520
  I'd better have baboons chattering
 and coolies beat their wives.

736
01:16:11,000 --> 01:16:14,640
Still the same old Peter. 
 Still playing with your pocket knife.

737
01:16:16,160 --> 01:16:18,880
  It is delicious, isn't it?

738
01:16:19,000 --> 01:16:23,920
  We are not all the same, Peter. 
 My husband may have his own cotton mill now,

739
01:16:23,960 --> 01:16:26,800
  but he was a miner's son
 and when he...

740
01:16:28,560 --> 01:16:33,720
 Oh, look! Look! 
 Isn't that Hugh Whitbread?

741
01:16:34,240 --> 01:16:38,520
 What a toady! 
 What an obsequious toady!

742
01:16:38,640 --> 01:16:40,040
  He's not changed at all.

743
01:16:40,960 --> 01:16:42,400
  How can she bear him?

744
01:16:45,480 --> 01:16:47,320
  It still makes you angry!

745
01:16:48,880 --> 01:16:53,160
  Look at her. Intoxicated, 
while they all're thinking she's brilliant.

746
01:16:53,880 --> 01:16:58,800
  Don't be too hard on her. 
 After all, parties are a kind of performance.

747
01:16:58,840 --> 01:17:02,040
  She has to give a performance. 
 It isn't the real Clarissa.

748
01:17:02,320 --> 01:17:06,360
  The real Clarissa was lost 
 years ago.

749
01:17:06,800 --> 01:17:09,400
  Mr. Prime Minister, can I 
 introduce our daughter.

750
01:17:09,440 --> 01:17:13,160
  I'm sure, if you were alone 
 with her, you'll find the old Clarissa again.

751
01:17:13,200 --> 01:17:14,840
  Fat chance of that this evening!

752
01:17:16,880 --> 01:17:19,960
  Richard so enjoyed your lunch and party.

753
01:17:20,000 --> 01:17:25,040
  Richard was most encouraging. 
 And he's promised to drop my little idea ...

754
01:17:25,080 --> 01:17:26,360
  into the right ear.

755
01:17:26,360 --> 01:17:30,920
  He and the Prime Minister 
 are having a quiet word now before he leaves.

756
01:17:30,960 --> 01:17:33,240
  My plan will save  
 the government a fortune.

757
01:17:33,400 --> 01:17:37,360
  Maybe Richard is sowing  
 the seeds this very minute.

758
01:17:39,240 --> 01:17:42,120
  Isn't that Peter Walsh 
 talking to old Mrs. Perry?

759
01:17:42,400 --> 01:17:44,280
  Yes, that's Peter.

760
01:17:44,960 --> 01:17:48,480
  Dear Peter. 
 So very sharp and clever...

761
01:17:48,520 --> 01:17:52,800
  sure had made a name for himself. But 
 he's allways in some trouble with women.

762
01:17:54,560 --> 01:17:56,200
  Do come and say hello to him!

763
01:17:57,880 --> 01:18:01,680
  Now, Peter, we can get it straight
 from the horse's mouth.

764
01:18:01,680 --> 01:18:03,800
  What is going on in India?

765
01:18:05,400 --> 01:18:09,600
 Well, great deal, Lady Bruton. 
 Is a very complex issue.

766
01:18:09,880 --> 01:18:11,120
  It is a tragedy.

767
01:18:11,480 --> 01:18:14,680
  If my father, the general, 
 would be alive, he'll sort it out.

768
01:18:14,760 --> 01:18:15,960
  Hay, Mrs. Perry.

769
01:18:18,720 --> 01:18:20,880
  Clarissa, I must speak with you, please ...

770
01:18:20,920 --> 01:18:24,360
  Peter, I must go and deal  
with Sir William and Lady Bradshaw.

771
01:18:24,400 --> 01:18:26,600
  Will talk later. 
 I promise.

772
01:18:32,120 --> 01:18:33,840
 Awfully good of you to come.

773
01:18:33,840 --> 01:18:37,720
  We are shockingly late. 
 We hardly dared to come in.

774
01:18:37,760 --> 01:18:39,720
  We couldn't resist the temptation.

775
01:18:40,080 --> 01:18:45,320
  But a rather sad occurrence held us up. 
 A young patient of mine killed himself.

776
01:18:45,440 --> 01:18:48,400
  Really, Richard, there must be 
 some provision ...

777
01:18:48,440 --> 01:18:51,400
  in the government's bill for 
this cases of delayed shell shock.

778
01:18:51,920 --> 01:18:56,840
  Yes, poor young man. 
Awarded for bravery during the war.

779
01:18:56,880 --> 01:19:01,280
  And than this evening he just throws himself
 out of the window. Impaled on the railings.

780
01:19:01,400 --> 01:19:02,800
  It's quite upset William.

781
01:19:02,840 --> 01:19:05,840
  She looks like a sea lion 
 barking at me.

782
01:19:05,880 --> 01:19:08,760
  Dear William. He does so hate 
 losing a patient.

783
01:19:08,800 --> 01:19:11,800
  When a young man's body is blown appart, 
 he loses an arm or a leg ...

784
01:19:11,800 --> 01:19:14,400
  or half of face, 
 as we've seen so often it.

785
01:19:14,480 --> 01:19:15,440
  It's immediate.

786
01:19:15,480 --> 01:19:20,480
  Stop it! Stop it! Don't talk of death 
 in the middle of my party!

787
01:19:20,520 --> 01:19:23,280
 I don't like you. 
 I've never liked you.

788
01:19:23,320 --> 01:19:25,960
  You're obscurely evil.

789
01:19:26,000 --> 01:19:28,960
 And the poor creature will either survive or he won't,
  but we all know ...

790
01:19:29,000 --> 01:19:30,000
 and we do our best for him.

791
01:19:30,040 --> 01:19:33,280
  A young man came to you 
on the edge of  insanity...

792
01:19:33,320 --> 01:19:35,640
  and you forced his soul ...

793
01:19:35,680 --> 01:19:40,120
 made his life intolerable 
 and he killed himself.

794
01:19:40,160 --> 01:19:44,520
 Stucked there with lobs... It's frightful... 
 Every single mother does everything ...

795
01:19:56,920 --> 01:20:00,200
  If you'll excuse me, 
 lady Bradshaw ...

796
01:20:04,800 --> 01:20:07,600
  I have to ... 
 Alice!

797
01:20:07,640 --> 01:20:11,080
  The problem is that politicians 
 are not really ...

798
01:20:11,120 --> 01:20:14,920
 very interested in shell shock. 
This is it. This is exactly it.

799
01:20:28,840 --> 01:20:32,400
  Hello, Henry, Eleonore. 
 Delightful to see you.

800
01:20:36,880 --> 01:20:40,480
  I see that sir William Bradshaw 
 is just arrived.

801
01:20:40,480 --> 01:20:44,920
I think it would be most useful to bring him in 
 on your emigration scheme.

802
01:20:44,960 --> 01:20:48,480
  I know he's treating many of this fellows
 from shell shock or whatever.

803
01:20:48,520 --> 01:20:51,960
  I'm sure, he'll think it's a good idea 
to get some of them to Canada.

804
01:20:52,000 --> 01:20:55,400
  Open air life and all that... 
excellent for mental disturbance.

805
01:20:55,440 --> 01:20:57,200
  What a good idea, Hugh.

806
01:21:07,800 --> 01:21:09,040
  She's disappeared.

807
01:21:11,000 --> 01:21:13,640
  Do you think she went upstairs? 
She can't have gone to bed, can't she?

808
01:21:13,680 --> 01:21:15,960
  No. She couldn't leave 
 her own party.

809
01:21:16,000 --> 01:21:18,440
 I don't know. I don't know.
 I didn't know she'd been ill.

810
01:21:18,960 --> 01:21:21,480
  Stop worrying, Peter.

811
01:21:23,400 --> 01:21:29,440
 He threw himself out of the window 
 and impaled himself on the railings.

812
01:21:29,640 --> 01:21:32,800
 Up flashed the ground 
 and through him ...

813
01:21:32,840 --> 01:21:36,760
  blundering and bruising 
 went the rusty spikes ...

814
01:21:36,800 --> 01:21:40,480
  and there he lay with a tut... tut! tut!
in his brain.

815
01:21:40,480 --> 01:21:44,120
  and then 
 a suffocation of blackness.

816
01:21:45,440 --> 01:21:47,960
  Why? Why did he do it?

817
01:21:48,080 --> 01:21:51,400
  Why did the Bradshaws talked 
 of it at my party?

818
01:21:51,440 --> 01:21:56,640
  He's thrown it all away. His life. 
 Just like that.

819
01:21:57,600 --> 01:22:01,760
  I once throw a shelling 
 into the serpentine.

820
01:22:02,640 --> 01:22:05,520
  But his thrown his life away.

821
01:22:07,560 --> 01:22:09,400
  You were going to write, 
 I remember.

822
01:22:11,680 --> 01:22:13,280
 Have you written anything?

823
01:22:17,640 --> 01:22:19,200
  Not a word.

824
01:22:21,840 --> 01:22:23,800
  Not a solitary word.

825
01:22:25,760 --> 01:22:30,600
  But then he will
 always stay young.

826
01:22:31,080 --> 01:22:37,560
 All day long I've been thinking 
of Bordon, of Peter and Sally.

827
01:22:37,720 --> 01:22:39,280
  We've grown old.

828
01:22:40,240 --> 01:22:42,000
  We'll grow older.

829
01:22:57,080 --> 01:22:59,160
  Have I lost the thing
 that mattered?

830
01:22:59,480 --> 01:23:02,720
  Let it get obscured, 
 gradually...

831
01:23:02,760 --> 01:23:08,280
  every day in corruption, 
 lies and chatter?

832
01:23:16,240 --> 01:23:18,800
  Do you remember the night 
 we went boating on the lake?

833
01:23:24,560 --> 01:23:27,120
  Yes, I remember thinking: 
 "She's abandoned me."

834
01:23:27,760 --> 01:23:33,200
  And then, all of the sudden, she was there, 
with her hand stretched out ...

835
01:23:34,520 --> 01:23:37,520
looking utterly beautiful, saying: 
 "Come on, come on.

836
01:23:37,560 --> 01:23:38,800
  They're all waiting. "

837
01:23:48,080 --> 01:23:50,520
  Why wouldn't she marry me, 
 Sally?

838
01:23:52,000 --> 01:23:53,320
  She was afraid.

839
01:23:58,760 --> 01:24:02,320
  Your parents just handed to you, 
 LIFE...

840
01:24:02,320 --> 01:24:05,720
  to be lived right through to the end.

841
01:24:06,320 --> 01:24:08,520
 We must walk it 
serenely.

842
01:24:08,640 --> 01:24:11,480
  But in the depths of my heart, 
 there's been an awful fear ...

843
01:24:11,520 --> 01:24:13,440
sometimes that 
 I couldn't go on ...

844
01:24:13,840 --> 01:24:18,320
  without Richard, sitting there
calmly reading the Times ...

845
01:24:18,360 --> 01:24:22,920
  while I crouched like a bird
and gradually revived.

846
01:24:22,960 --> 01:24:24,880
  I might have perished.

847
01:24:28,880 --> 01:24:32,720
  I looked across the room 
 and wondered - "Who's that lovely girl?"

848
01:24:33,000 --> 01:24:36,640
  And then I realized: 
 "That's my daughter."

849
01:24:39,440 --> 01:24:42,400
  Maybe she needed someone
 who found life simple.

850
01:24:44,320 --> 01:24:47,640
  She certainly cared for you, 
 more than she cared for Richard.

851
01:24:49,320 --> 01:24:50,960
  Oh, my life isn't simple.

852
01:24:52,080 --> 01:24:56,160
  My relationship with her
 wasn't simple.

853
01:24:59,480 --> 01:25:01,080
  She broke my heart.

854
01:25:02,800 --> 01:25:06,080
  And you can't love like that 
 twice.

855
01:25:08,120 --> 01:25:09,840
  What makes us go on?

856
01:25:11,480 --> 01:25:14,640
  What sends roaring 
 up in us ...

857
01:25:14,680 --> 01:25:17,840
  that immeasurable delight
 to surprise us?

858
01:25:18,080 --> 01:25:20,600
Than nothing can be 
slow enough...

859
01:25:20,640 --> 01:25:22,720
  nothing lasts to long.

860
01:25:22,920 --> 01:25:27,480
 You want to say to each moment: 
 "Stay!" "Stay!"

861
01:25:28,000 --> 01:25:29,320
  "Stay!"

862
01:25:45,920 --> 01:25:49,040
I cherrish the friendship
 I had with Clarissa.

863
01:25:50,040 --> 01:25:51,960
 There was something pure about her.

864
01:25:52,760 --> 01:25:57,600
  She had such charm, 
 such generosity.

865
01:25:57,640 --> 01:26:01,560
  I can see her to this day, going 
 bye the house all in white.

866
01:26:02,320 --> 01:26:06,560
She always seemed to be in white 
and her arms were full of flowers.

867
01:26:07,120 --> 01:26:08,640
  And I wondered ...

868
01:26:10,080 --> 01:26:11,840
  does absence really matter?

869
01:26:12,760 --> 01:26:14,080
  Does distance?

870
01:26:16,520 --> 01:26:19,880
  You'll think me sentimental 
 and so I am ...

871
01:26:20,200 --> 01:26:24,920
  but I've come to believe that the only 
 thing worth saying is what you really feel.

872
01:26:27,040 --> 01:26:29,080
 But I don't know what I feel.

873
01:26:30,920 --> 01:26:35,400
  I know that I loved her once 
 and that it stayed with me all my life ...

874
01:26:35,440 --> 01:26:37,600
  and colored everything.

875
01:26:39,960 --> 01:26:44,400
  I must go back to my party. 
To Sally and Peter.

876
01:26:47,040 --> 01:26:50,520
  That young man killed himself, 
 but I don't pity him.

877
01:26:50,560 --> 01:26:53,560
  I'm somehow glad he could do it, 
throw it away.

878
01:26:54,400 --> 01:26:58,960
 It's made me feel the beauty, 
 somehow feel ...

879
01:26:59,040 --> 01:27:03,440
very like him, less afraid.

880
01:27:11,480 --> 01:27:12,720
  I have to go.

881
01:27:19,720 --> 01:27:23,440
  Do you think he's made her happy? 
 Who can tell, Peter?

882
01:27:23,840 --> 01:27:28,240
  All our relationships are 
 just scratches on the surface.

883
01:27:29,000 --> 01:27:31,560
  We tought he wasn't 
 very bright.

884
01:27:31,600 --> 01:27:34,120
  But what does the brain matter?

885
01:27:36,800 --> 01:27:38,480
  Compared to the heart.

886
01:28:20,680 --> 01:28:22,040
  There you are.

887
01:28:24,040 --> 01:28:28,320
  Peter and Sally haven't left, have they? 
 Don't know.

888
01:28:29,200 --> 01:28:30,600
  Clarissa!

889
01:28:34,200 --> 01:28:36,360
  I couldn't leave without 
saying goodbye.

890
01:28:36,840 --> 01:28:40,080
And you can't leave, 
 until you danced with me.

891
01:28:48,360 --> 01:28:49,880
  Peter's in the library.

892
01:29:11,800 --> 01:29:13,840
  Here I am, at last.

893
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
 
